The paper deals with an online matching problem in a metric space, which involves designing algorithms that make decisions based on partial information. This is a fundamental problem in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The problem also has connections to game theory (cs.GT) since the algorithm has to make strategic decisions to minimize the cost of matching. The use of delays in the matching process suggests that the algorithm needs to reason about the future, which is a key aspect of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The cost function involves distances and delays, which are both related to information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the problem has applications in scheduling and resource allocation, which are topics in systems and control (cs.SI).
